    <h1>PLANTS ARE PLECTRANTH&#xAD;US SPECIES</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201205/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-05"><time>2020-12-05</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | DESIGN</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>I was given these mint plants. What are their names and are they ed­i­ble? Gan Sing Hai</p>
    <p>The plant on the left is botan­i­cally known as Plectranth­us zey­lan­i­cus. It is not to be mis­taken for its close rel­a­tive, shown on the right, the In­dian bor­age (Plectranth­us am­boini­cus), though the two species look very sim­i­lar.</p>
    <p>Lo­cally, this plant is some­times called “lemon balm” due to its cit­rusy scent.</p>
    <p>How­ever, the true Lemon Balm (Melissa of­fic­i­nalis) is an­other plant species al­to­gether. This plant is used in ayurvedic medicine.</p>
    <p>The plant on the right is the var­ie­gated ver­sion of the In­dian bor­age. Its leaves are some­times used as an oregano sub­sti­tute and, lo­cally, they are boiled and the tea drunk to treat coughs.</p>

